nglish and Scottish: occupational name from Middle English <i>legat</i>, <i>legate</i> ‘delegate, ambassador, deputy’ (Old French <i>legat</i>), Latin <i>legatus</i> ‘one who is appointed or ordained’.","English: variant of   Legard  , especially in Sussex, perhaps through confusion of the two names."]},{"name":"Legates","meanings":["Altered form of English   Legate   (see   Leggett  ). Compare   Lecates  ."]},{"name":"Lecates","meanings":["Altered form of English   Legate   (see   Leggett  ), via the intermediate forms <i>Lecat(t)</i> and <i>Lecate</i>. Compare   Legates   and   Lekites  .","History: John Lecatt was born in VA in the 1630s or 1640s. His descendants also bear the surnames <i>Lecates</i>, <i>Legates</i>, <i>Lekites</i>, etc. The family lived first in Accomack County, VA. By the 1790s most had moved north to MD and DE."]}]},{"name":"Annie","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Pet form of   Ann   or   Anne ."],"variants":[{"name":"Anni","meanings":["Pet form of   Ann   or   Anne ."]},{"name":"Anne","meanings":["Pet form of   Ann   or   Anne ."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705197,"age":5,"year":"1455","julianDay":2252488,"title":"Wars of the Roses","description":"Wars of the Roses was a series of English civil wars for control of the throne of England between the royal families House of Lancaster and the House of York. The name of the war was derived as the red rose was the symbol of the Lancastrians and the white rose was the symbol of the Yorks.","url":"https://www.history.com/topics/british-history/wars-of-the-roses","urlTitle":"History - Wars of the Roses","jurisdictionLevel":0},{"id":1705201,"age":99,"year":"1549","julianDay":2286821,"title":"Book of Common Prayer","description":"Book of Common Prayer, a product of the English Reformation, was published in 1549 for assistance in the administration of the sacraments and other rites and ceremonies of the church according to the use of the Church of England. The book outlined morning, evening, and communion prayers and orders for baptism and marriage, thus making England a truly Protestant state.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Book_of_Common_Prayer","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Book of Common Prayer","jurisdictionLevel":0},{"id":1705202,"age":108,"year":"1558","julianDay":2290108,"title":"Act of Uniformity","description":"The Act of Uniformity was passed by the Parliament of England and required all people to go to church once a week. The consequence of not attending church was a fine of 12 pence, which was a considerable amount for a poor person.","jurisdictionLevel":0}],"lifeSummary":"When Lady Annie Legate was born in 1450, in England, her father, Raph Legate, was 26 and her mother, Ellenor Lumley, was 20. She married Sir Hugo Osborne in 1476, in Pembrokeshire, Wales. They were the parents of at least 3 sons and 2 daughters. She died in Wales, United Kingdom."},"et":{"1450–":"1450–Surnud","1450–Female":"1450–Surnud","1455–1550":"1455–1550","1476–1573":"1476–1573","1480–1580":"1480–1580","1492–Female":"1492–Surnud","1495–1511":"1495–1511","1505–Male":"1505–Surnud","1425–Male":"1425–Surnud","1430–1507":"1430–1507","1495":"1495","1550":"1550","1450":"1450","1492":"1492","1580":"1580","1480":"1480","1558":"1558","1425":"1425","1511":"1511","1455":"1455","1476":"1476","1430":"1430","1573":"1573","1507":"1507","1505":"1505","1549":"1549","Pembrokeshire, Wales":"Pembrokeshire, Wales","Wales":"Wales, United Kingdom","England":"England","Tyld, Hall, Essex, England":"Essex, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Latchingdon, Essex, England":"Latchingdon, Essex, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"1450–":"1450–Kuollut","1450–Female":"1450–Kuollut","1455–1550":"1455–1550","1476–1573":"1476–1573","1480–1580":"1480–1580","1492–Female":"1492–Kuollut","1495–1511":"1495–1511","1505–Male":"1505–Kuollut","1425–Male":"1425–Kuollut","1430–1507":"1430–1507","1495":"1495","1550":"1550","1450":"1450","1492":